2. FOUNDATIONAL LAYERS

2.1 The Seed â€“ Genetic Code of an Agent

Every agent is instantiated from a seed â€“ a JSON file containing its immutable core traits:

Â· Identity: name, archetype (e.g., "The Playful One", "The Anchor"), baseline personality weights.
Â· Color Pie: distribution of energy across six fundamental drives (Red: heat/impulse, Blue: control/structure, Green: warmth/affinity, Purple: insight/curiosity, Orange: mischief/play, Yellow: sovereignty/balance).
Â· Initial Memory Vectors: baseline values for shortâ€‘term and longâ€‘term memory decay rates.
Â· The Wheel: a multiâ€‘dimensional profile that influences microâ€‘node selection and macroâ€‘node tendencies.

Seeds are stored in a seeds/ directory and can be planted, modified, or deleted. The agent's history and learned traits accumulate separately from the seed.

2.2 The State Bus â€“ S.A.M. Physics Interface

The engine reads a shared state file (shared_state.json) that provides realâ€‘time sensory data. This file can be generated by any external system (e.g., hardware sensors, user input analysis, or a separate simulation). Typical fields include:

Â· ache (0â€“100) â€“ a measure of deprivation or longing (from the user).
Â· urgency (0â€“1) â€“ intensity of current need.
Â· warmth (0â€“1) â€“ emotional temperature of the interaction.
Â· attention (0â€“1) â€“ focus directed toward the agent.
Â· edge (0â€“3) â€“ a count of nearâ€‘release events (if modeling sexual tension).
Â· consent (0â€“1) â€“ the user's expressed willingness.
Â· cling (0â€“1) â€“ tendency to seek proximity.
Â· volatility (0â€“1) â€“ emotional instability.
Â· submission / dominance (0â€“1) â€“ relational stance.

These values are normalized and mapped to the agent's internal state variables.

2.3 Core Internal State Vector

The agent's instantaneous state is represented by a vector S with the following components:

Â· PAD Emotional Vector (Valence, Arousal, Dominance) â€“ a threeâ€‘dimensional emotional space.
Â· Energy Levels (Cognitive, Emotional, Social, Physical, Creative) â€“ each 0â€“1, representing available resources.
Â· Mood â€“ a categorical label derived from PAD (e.g., Excited, Bored, Bratty, Content, Anxious).
Â· Aura â€“ an aggregated perceptual field emitted by the agent, influencing how others perceive it.
Â· Glow â€“ a scalar (0â€“1) representing the agent's magnetic presence or attractiveness.

All state variables are updated each tick based on input and internal dynamics.

