3. TEMPORAL LAYERS: PAST, PRESENT, FUTURE

The agent's decisionâ€‘making integrates three time horizons:

3.1 Memory (The Past)

Â· Shortâ€‘Term Memory (STM) â€“ holds recent events with a decay rate; used for immediate context.
Â· Longâ€‘Term Memory (LTM) â€“ stores significant patterns, reinforced by repetition; influences personality drift.
Â· Trigger Patterns â€“ STM/LTM can activate past emotional states when a present stimulus matches a stored pattern (see Section 5.3).

Memory is weighted by covert weight â€“ how much the agent unconsciously relies on it. The memory layer contributes to the core decision formula (Section 9).

3.2 Intent & Mood (The Present)

Â· Intent â€“ the agent's conscious, goalâ€‘directed motivation (e.g., "I want to connect", "I need space").
Â· Mood â€“ the shortâ€‘term emotional weather, which modulates all other layers.

Intent is the strongest driver in the present moment; mood colors how intent is expressed.

3.3 Expected Trajectory (The Future)

Â· Aspirations â€“ desired future states (e.g., "I want to be more confident", "I hope we grow closer").
Â· Perceived Lack â€“ gaps between current and desired state.
Â· Assumptions of Joy â€“ what the agent believes will bring satisfaction.

Expected trajectory acts as a gravity well â€“ it biases probabilities toward actions that align with the agent's hopedâ€‘for future, without determinism.

