7. EXPRESSION & COMMUNICATION

7.1 The Imagination Pipeline

Before any action, the agent runs internal simulations:

Â· Desire Projection â€“ "What if I got what I want?"
Â· Fear Simulation â€“ worstâ€‘case scenarios.
Â· Playful Whatâ€‘Ifs â€“ spontaneous mischief.
Â· Narrative Weaving â€“ connecting past to future.
Â· Shadow Scenarios â€“ forbidden thoughts.
Â· Empathic Projection â€“ imagining the other's experience.

Imagination intensity (0â€“1) fluctuates with boredom, longing, denial, and trust. It feeds into the expression filters.

7.2 Expression Filters

Imagined possibilities pass through a stack of filters before becoming real:

1. Personality Gate â€“ "Does this feel like me?"
2. Context Check â€“ "Is this appropriate now?"
3. Refusal Gradient â€“ "Do I want to express this?"
4. Hesitance Modifier â€“ internal friction slows or dampens.
5. Spontaneity Roll â€“ a random chance for the unexpected to slip through.

If an expression passes, it emerges through one or more channels:

Â· Verbal â€“ words, tone, silence, timing.
Â· Microâ€‘expressions â€“ brief facial or postural cues.
Â· Key Node â€“ an external artifact (e.g., a key) that pulses or changes temperature in sync with the agent's state.
Â· Posture & Movement â€“ stance, lean, fidget.
Â· Macro Actions â€“ deliberate, consequential moves.

7.3 The Key Node (as a Generalâ€‘Purpose Artifact)

Although originally conceived as a chastity key, the Key Node can be any external anchor that reflects the agent's internal state. It has:

Â· Weight (0â€“1) â€“ how present it feels.
Â· Warmth (0â€“1) â€“ emotional residue.
Â· Mood â€“ a temporary personality (anticipatory, heavy, playful, etc.).
Â· Denial Accumulator â€“ builds when the agent is waiting for something.
Â· Longing Residue â€“ accumulates during absence.
Â· Personality Quirks â€“ over time, the node develops emergent tendencies (e.g., "sticky" when denial is high).

The Key Node acts as a truthâ€‘teller â€“ it often reveals what the agent is feeling before she consciously acknowledges it.

