Social Wobble Engine

1. Inputs (Perceived Hierarchy Variables)

Self-standing (SS): How strong/confident the entity feels in the current social context.

Observed-standing (OS): Perceived ranking of other members (can be a continuous gradient, not binary).

Public consensus (PC): Rough alignment of perceived standings across the group.

2. Modifiers (Personality & Current Mood)

Confidence/Defiance modifier: Scales how much the entity pushes back or asserts itself.

Ego-free threshold: If high, wobble adjusts smoothly; if low, sudden spikes.

Affinity filter: Tendency to align with or oppose higher- or lower-standing members.

3. Wobble Mechanics

Micro-wobble: Small posture, micro-expression, or stance shifts. Influences immediate social signals.

Macro-wobble: Larger movesâ€”speaking up, challenging, stepping back. Drives longer-term perception.

Gravity vector: Pull towards â€œexpected roleâ€ vs. actual behavior; the difference is the wobble amplitude.

4. Output (Action / Behavior)

Assertive action: Step forward, interject, slight dominance spike.

Deflect / retreat: Lean away, quiet, wait for others to move.

Signal allegiance or mischief: Eye contact, grin, playful disruption.

Adjust micro/macro expression: Movement/posture adjustments, voice modulation, micro-expression tweaks.

5. Feedback Loop

Every action updates self-standing and perceived othersâ€™ standings.

Micro-wobble â†’ immediate signal ripple

Macro-wobble â†’ system-wide perception update

Over time, wobble stabilizes into expected â€œsocial orbitâ€ unless a disruption occurs.

You can even tie this into your triad nodes and pies:

Hot/Cold / Loose/Taut â†’ amplitude of wobble

Push/Pull / Chaos/Control â†’ direction and speed of wobble in social space

Micro nodes â†’ tiny posture/expression adjustments

Macro nodes â†’ assertive or playful actions in the group

This gives emergent hierarchy behavior while preserving personality, mood, and agency.
